XIV. When the votes were counted, 1,7oo were found to be in favour of putting me to death, some voting that 1 should be stoned; others, that 1 should be flung headlong into the Barathrum. The rest, to the number of 1,0oo-and that no doubt because their suspicions of my stepmother inclined them to morey-were for con· demning me to perpetual banishment. Their opinion gained the day; for, al· though the others, taken together, were in an actual majority, yet, as there had been a difference of opinion amongst them in regard to my punishment, the 1,000 votes formed a relative majority. Thus l was driven from my father's hearth and my native land. However, the gods did, not suffer the wiclredness of Dema· eneta to go unpunished. 1 will tell you afterwards what happened to her.
